related_questions.question: How is sherry different from wine?
related_questions.snippet: Sherry is basically an aged white wine and contrary to what most people think, the majority of sherry is dry. Within the dry sherry category, there are two major styles: those that are biologically aged (under a layer of flor yeast – Fino type) and those that are oxidatively aged (in absence of flor – Oloroso type).
related_questions.title: Sherry types: dry and sweet styles | SherryNotes

related_questions.question: What does sherry taste like?
related_questions.snippet: Fino and Manzanilla Sherry Their alcohol content is 15% abv and has a crisp, tangy, yeasty and nutty flavour profile. Fino Sherry is very dry with delicate acidity which leaves a pleasant and fresh aftertaste of almonds. Manzanilla is a fino-style sherry, which has a distinctive salty tang and is fresher than Fino.
related_questions.title: What Does Dry Sherry Taste Like | Learn About Spain's Fortified Wine

related_questions.question: What is a sherry?
related_questions.snippet: Sherry is a drink produced in a variety of styles made primarily from the Palomino grape, ranging from light versions similar to white table wines, such as Manzanilla and fino, to darker and heavier versions that have been allowed to oxidise as they age in barrel, such as Amontillado and oloroso.
related_questions.title: Sherry - Wikipedia

related_questions.question: Is sherry very alcoholic?
related_questions.snippet: Sherry is a highly alcoholic wine, ranging from 15% ABV to an incredibly boozy 22%. This means it is often enjoyed at the end or beginning of a meal, similar to Port. However, traditionally, Spanish wine lovers would park a nice glass of Sherry on the side of their tapas.

buttons.snippet: Sherry is a complex category of wine that encompasses seven different styles. These are manzanilla, fino, amontillado, oloroso, palo cortado, cream and Pedro Ximénez.

buttons.subtitle: How Sweet Is Sherry
buttons.title: Medium / Cream sherry: a sweet blended style | SherryNotes
buttons.snippet: Types of sweet sherry A well-known example of this style is the Croft sherry. Medium sherry contains between 5 and 115 grams of sugar per liter. It is often composed around Amontillado, sometimes with a small amount of Oloroso added to it, as well as Moscatel and/or Pedro Ximénez. Cream sherry is between 115–140 grams.
snippet_highlighted_words: between 5 and 115 grams of sugar per liter

buttons.subtitle: What Is Sherry Used For?
buttons.title: What is Sherry and How Do I Use It?
buttons.snippet: Here are its best uses: To deglaze a pan– after searing meats, sherry is an excellent choice for deglazing the pan. It makes an excellent pan sauce. To brighten soups and stews– just a splash of sherry right before serving can give a nice kick to many cream and broth based soups.

buttons.subtitle: What Is Sherry Made Of?
buttons.title: Everything You Need to Know About Sherry Wine
buttons.snippet: Sherry is wine made from white grapes. The grape variety Palomino features prominently in dry versions, while sweet versions like cream sherry might include Pedro Ximénez (PX) and Moscatel. Sherries are aged in a unique system called the solera, where barrels of fortified wines sit for years at ambient temperatures.

buttons.subtitle: Cooking Sherry
buttons.title: What's the Difference Between Cooking Sherry, Dry ... - MasterClass
buttons.snippet: Cooking sherry is a grape wine fortified with brandy, just like regular sherry. To extend its shelf life, salt is added, as well as potassium metabisulfite and potassium sorbate. Cooking sherry is used specifically as a culinary ingredient to add a sweet and nutty taste to food.
snippet_highlighted_words: a grape wine fortified with brandy

buttons.subtitle: Is Sherry Dry Or Sweet
buttons.title: A Handy Chart for Categorizing Sherry - Alcademics
buttons.snippet: Oloroso, Amontillado, and Palo Cortado sherries are either dry (without a sweetness label) or labelled as Dry, Medium, or Cream. Fino and Manzanilla sherries, when sweetened, are often sweetened with rectified wine musts instead of PX/Moscatel (because those wines are dark and would alter the color of the wine).
snippet_highlighted_words: either dry (without a sweetness label) or labelled as Dry, Medium, or Cream
